<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<appendix xml:id="ap-axioms-of-real-numbers" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Axioms of Real Numbers</title>

  <section xml:id="sec-axioms-foundations">
    <title>Foundations and Consequences</title>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-axioms-ordered-field">
      <title>Ordered-Field Axioms</title>

      <p>
        We start with a set <m>\R</m> with two operations <m>+</m> and <m>\cdot</m>, and a subset
        <m>\R_{+}\subseteq \R</m>. We call this an <term>ordered field</term><idx>ordered field</idx>
        when the following hold.
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>+</m> and <m>\cdot</m> are commutative and associative, and
            <m>a(b+c)=ab+ac</m> for all <m>a,b,c\in\R</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            There are distinct elements <m>0,1\in\R</m> such that
            <m>a+0=a</m> and <m>a\cdot 1=a</m> for all <m>a\in\R</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Every <m>a\in\R</m> has an additive inverse <m>-a</m> with
            <m>a+(-a)=0</m>, and every nonzero <m>a\in\R</m> has a multiplicative inverse
            <m>a^{-1}</m> with <m>a\cdot a^{-1}=1</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The set <m>\R_{+}</m> is closed under addition and multiplication.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            For each <m>a\in\R</m>, exactly one of <m>a=0</m>, <m>a\in\R_{+}</m>,
            <m>-a\in\R_{+}</m> holds.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        We define <m>a&lt;b</m> if and only if <m>b-a\in\R_{+}</m>, and
        <m>a\le b</m> if and only if <m>a&lt;b</m> or <m>a=b</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        To characterize the real numbers, we add the <term>least upper bound
        property</term><idx>least upper bound property</idx>: every nonempty subset of
        <m>\R</m> that is bounded above has a least upper bound in <m>\R</m>.
        An ordered field with this property is a <term>complete ordered
        field</term><idx>complete ordered field</idx>.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-axioms-isomorphism-reference">
      <title>Uniqueness Up to Isomorphism</title>

      <p>
        A standard theorem says that any two complete ordered fields are
        isomorphic (as ordered fields). This is the precise sense in which
        there is only one real number system up to isomorphism.
      </p>

      <p>
        Reference: <xref ref="biblio-rosenlicht-intro"/>, Chapter II, end of
        Section 4 (after the proof of existence of square roots), where he
        states that Properties I-VII determine the real number system up to a
        unique one-to-one correspondence preserving sums and products.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-axioms-immediate-consequences">
      <title>Immediate Consequences of the Axioms</title>

      <p>
        The next results are typical short derivations from the axioms
        (compare <xref ref="biblio-rosenlicht-intro"/>, Chapter II, Sections 1-2).
      </p>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-axioms-identity-inverse-uniqueness">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The additive identity and multiplicative identity are unique.
            For each <m>a\in\R</m>, the additive inverse <m>-a</m> is unique; if
            <m>a\ne0</m>, then the multiplicative inverse <m>a^{-1}</m> is unique.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            If <m>0,0'</m> are additive identities, then
            <m>0=0+0'=0'</m>. The same argument gives uniqueness of <m>1</m>.
            If <m>b,c</m> both satisfy <m>a+b=0</m> and <m>a+c=0</m>, then
            <m>b=b+0=b+(a+c)=(b+a)+c=0+c=c</m>. The multiplicative case is identical
            for <m>a\ne0</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </proposition>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-axioms-basic-algebra-consequences">
        <statement>
          <p>
            For every <m>a,b\in\R</m>:
            <m>a\cdot0=0</m>, <m>(-1)a=-a</m>, and
            <m>(-a)(-b)=ab</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Since <m>0+0=0</m>, distributivity gives
            <m>a\cdot0=a(0+0)=a\cdot0+a\cdot0</m>. Adding <m>-(a\cdot0)</m> to both
            sides yields <m>a\cdot0=0</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Next, <m>((-1)+1)a=(-1)a+a=0\cdot a=0</m>, so <m>(-1)a</m> is an additive
            inverse of <m>a</m>; by uniqueness, <m>(-1)a=-a</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Then <m>(-a)(-b)=((-1)a)((-1)b)=((-1)(-1))ab</m>. Also
            <m>((-1)+1)(-1)=0</m> gives <m>(-1)(-1)+(-1)=0</m>, hence
            <m>(-1)(-1)=1</m>. Therefore <m>(-a)(-b)=ab</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </proposition>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-axioms-basic-order-consequences">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>a&lt;b</m>, then <m>a+c&lt;b+c</m> for every <m>c\in\R</m>.
            If <m>a&lt;b</m> and <m>0&lt;c</m>, then <m>ac&lt;bc</m>.
            Also, <m>a^2\ge0</m> for every <m>a\in\R</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            If <m>a&lt;b</m>, then <m>b-a\in\R_{+}</m>. But
            <m>(b+c)-(a+c)=b-a\in\R_{+}</m>, so <m>a+c&lt;b+c</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            If additionally <m>0&lt;c</m>, then <m>c\in\R_{+}</m> and
            <m>b-a\in\R_{+}</m>. Closure of <m>\R_{+}</m> under multiplication gives
            <m>c(b-a)=bc-ac\in\R_{+}</m>, hence <m>ac&lt;bc</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            For <m>a\in\R</m>, exactly one of <m>a=0</m>, <m>a\in\R_{+}</m>,
            <m>-a\in\R_{+}</m> holds. If <m>a=0</m>, then <m>a^2=0</m>. Otherwise
            either <m>a^2\in\R_{+}</m> or <m>(-a)^2\in\R_{+}</m>, and
            <m>(-a)^2=a^2</m>. Thus <m>a^2</m> is never negative, i.e. <m>a^2\ge0</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </proposition>
    </subsection>
  </section>

</appendix>
